eVOGe" style=3D"direction:ltr"><span style=3D"color:rgb(33, 37, 41);font-si=
ze:undefined">The most reliable way to ensure your meat is cooked through i=
s by using a meat thermometer. Insert it into the thickest part of the meat=
, avoiding bones and fat, and check that it reaches the recommended interna=
l temperature. If some areas read lower, return the meat to the oven for at=
 least 10 minutes and recheck.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=3D"Text_m-SansReg__=
eVOGe" style=3D"direction:ltr"><span style=3D"color:rgb(33, 37, 41);font-si=
ze:undefined">Another way to check the level of doneness is by piercing the=
 meat with a spoon to inspect the juices. There shouldn=E2=80=99t be any tr=
aces of blood, and the liquid should run clear or golden. If your meat=E2=
=80=99s juices aren=E2=80=99t clear or golden, return the meat to the oven =
for five or more minutes.</span></p><p class=3D"Text_m-SansReg__eVOGe"><spa=
n style=3D"color:rgb(33, 37, 41);font-size:undefined">It=E2=80=99s also imp=
ortant to understand the "danger zone" (40=C2=B0F to 140=C2=B0F), where bac=
teria can rapidly grow. To prevent this, keep raw meat out of this temperat=
ure range and refrigerate promptly. After cooking, let the meat rest for fi=
ve to 10 minutes =E2=80=94 carryover cooking will raise the internal temper=
ature by 5-10=C2=B0F, ensuring it=E2=80=99s safe</span>.</p><h3 class=3D"Te=
xt_xl-ContrastSemi__1vI_l"><b class=3D"RichText_bold__GUmsN">Safe minimum i=
